HI Everyone,

This is my first post so bare with me.

I wanted to add a quick Note:
I wanted to say thank you to Jubaleth for the original designs, for posting and providing access to the onshape originals I did not have the printer experience to have created this from scratch this design is made possible by Him and I simply added to it.

As mentioned the design is largely based on Jubaleth's original design for the X-Carriage. Two of the main changes are that i removed the Z sensor mount. I use the standard rear mount bed Z sensor and the second change is that I redesigned the nozzle fan shroud.

I also added a second part witch was a 40mm fan shroud with integrated e3dv6 lock for the e3dv6 heat sink and vents the exhaust to the rear.

By all means please let me know if you have any comments. The fan shroud is a little tricky to get the angle on the bed to print without to many supports (as mentioned below).

I have also designed the rear y-belt bracket and z sensor mount witch I will list as separate projects as they are independent to the X-Carriage and can be used separately.

You will also notice 4 holes in the top of the 40mm fan shroud, these are for a y-belt bracket i designed and am printing now to test and will post all the y-chain pieces in a separate project.

Notes:

I printed this High Quality (.1) but see no reasons why it would not work at medium quality.

Main Carriage:
Material: PLA
Bed temp: 65C
Hot End: 210C

I have used 15 - 30% infill and found 15% strong enough. No Supports (print on its back).

For the Fan:
Printed with supports (from build platform only). You will have to rotate the drawing until it is lieing on its back at approx. 3.23 degrees so that it is lieing as flat as possible fan outlet facing up.

Assembly

Some of the holes for the threaded parts (self threaded) can be a bit tight but all work with a little force to get the bolt thread started.

I did have to get slightly longer 8m screws to screw the X-Carriage base to the bearing houses but this was because several of my threads in the bearings were poorly don't by the manufacture and stripped out on first install. the rest of the install used screws that came with the kit. I would expect your original screws to work fine if your bearing threads are in good shape.

Other than the above a little trimming and a slight counter sinking of the holes to be threaded to help the screws start is all that needs to be done. I just used a Philips screw driver to do the counter sinking.

I created this using OnShape.com (fantastic online cad design application)

I had a spare Teensy 2.0 and some 8mm led Neopixels lying around so I decided to build a space invader sculpture that would live (invade) the space on top of my computer. It usually takes me a few shots to design an object to my liking. I designed two Space Invaders (one is anatomically correct) and the other (pictured) is less so. I posted both STL files. I also posted "add ons" which can be used with some superglue to make the prototype more accurate. The idea is to backlight the "space invader" and to have a project box, background to house electronics. This is a really neat thing to put on top of a lit computer fan. It looks cool.

I have teensy running the stock Neopixel test script. If you notice I also have a speaker pictured in the background of one shot. Since I am only using power, ground, and signal pins the combinations of how your Space Invader can perform is endless. I might program the light show to do the accelerating Space Invader background sound. I constructed the Space Invader to be solderless by using a cheap breadboard and some dupont cables. PS it would be great to have an "animated invader" using small motors or servo's. The Teensy is a great device and it is great for "makers."

The "with ears" version is the anatomically correct version. The Neopixels fit into 8mm holes and then are glued in place from the back. The dupont wires fit over the Neopixel leads.

These are great because they have an input pin, positive, ground, and output pin. You can you a really small Arduino device because you only need one pin for signal with the leds chained to each other.

I could have put a capacitor between Positive and ground; but decided not to.

description.text:
After looking on here for a bit to find a decent Mini Disc model, all I found is what appeared to be scans of LARGE discs, shrunk down to mini size. This ran into all kinds of problems of the walls being really thin, flimsy mini discs, etc... Being an avid disc golfer as well, and the son of a mechanical engineer, I decided to got to CAD and create my own.

Voila! And here we have a mini disc that is more like an ACTUAL mini disc in size and substance. It has a rounded curve on the top part of the disc, with a straight line under on the base. The two different files vary only by the underside of the disc. On the inside of the rim, one goes straight up to a 90 degree angle, the other has a chamfered curve up to the bottom of the disc.

If you have something like 123D Designer, you can easily merge something onto the top of this to make your own custom embossed mini discs (that is actually what I came up with the design for).

This can be printed in any filament you prefer, but I ended up doing them in ABS with the intent to use an Acetone Vapor Bath to give them a smoother, shinier look.

IF YOU PRINT THIS, LIKE THIS, AND WOULD LIKE TO HELP ME OUT MAYBE GO INTO THIS AS A BUSINESS, PLEASE CHECK OUT: https://www.gofundme.com/gobiggolittle

Monoprice Mini Select

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Notes:

These settings are what I used because I have many people ordering a customized version of this. You can print this with or without supports. If you are printing it BLANK, you can print it upside down for better results.

I am using Slic3r for creating the GCode, and in that I am using a 1.1 multiplier for the final extrusion to make sure it gets all the little cracks and crevices covered. Also using concentric for the top and bottom infill settings, honeycomb for the rest.

Using ABS Filament
First Layer:
Extruder Heat: 235
Heat Bed: 105

Other Layers:
Extruder Heat: 230
Heat Bed: 100

Sand, Sand, and Vapor Bath

These turn out REALLY nicely with a little post processing. After using a craft knife to remove any pieces of the raft left on, I use a woodburning stencil transfer tool (round, flat discs with curved up edges) to melt the underside where any fibers that didn't bridge well might be hanging down (printing with no supports underneath... could be remixed for a dual extruder with water-soluble supports to resolve this, but I don't have a dual extruder).

Once those are all smoothed down, I sand the sides and top once with a 100 grit sandpaper, and then a 220 grit or finer sand paper to smooth out the surfaces as much as possible. Then, I put the mini disc in an Acetone Vapor bath (using the cold method, paper towels inside a large glass container) for 45 minutes.

Once they come out of this, they still need a few minutes to dry and finish. Once they finish drying, they have a beautiful shiny candy-coat to them that also helps them solidify the outer shell for added strength.

title: Is your printer printing square? (Calibration test)

description.text:
Is your printer printing square?

Prusa owners likely wont have a problem, but CORE-XY and Kossels and other printers with complex math or flexible gantries are susceptible to 90 angles printing at 80-100 or anywhere between. This can cause problems if you want to print large structural parts, like an LCD screen holder, only to find the holes are skewed..

This simple model prints in less than 10 minutes and will let you know if youre ready to take on a big project with the help of a metal square/right angle, in X, Y, and Z.

It is 25x25x25mm, the posts being 5x5mm.

(For CORE-XY, like me, even slight changes in belt tension can skew the axes.)

I improved the canopy to fit and protect a HS1177/HS1190 with GoPro 2 lens without having canopy parts covering the fpv image. It is optimised to give the best strength to protect the electronics.   • Optimised for HS1177/HS1190 with GoPro lens.
  • FPV camera snaps in 3 different anglels (25, 40 and 50 degrees of tilt).
  • Optimized strength to protect electronics.
  • Heavy duty fixation to the frame with four M3 nuts to withstand impact from crashes.
  • Two versions; with or without GoPro HD cam mount (GoPro HD version is 5 grams heavier).
  • GoPro HD version is still low profile as possible (uses adapters to enlarge tilt of HD camera).
  • Canopy fits the Realacc X210 bottom plate and outlines (read below for a better unibody frame).
  • It's so beautiful!!

  • FPV Camera: HS1177 or HS1190 (or simular)

Why another CNC DIY more? After seeing all the CNC machines that people were building and shared the photos and videos on the internet, I was curious and started to investigate the subject. For me at the beginning it was a challenge to be able to build my own CNC and be able to mechanize my designs. Now, after building it, I would like to share the design and I would be glad to see other people build it.
 
The objectives of this CNC are:

  • Make it cheap and simple
  • Carry the largest number of pieces printed in 3D.
  • Precision of assembly to be pieces printed in 3D.
  • It is compact and sufficiently rigid to the extent that plastic parts can be printed in 3D
  • Mechanize wood, plastics, etc., in short soft materials. I have not tried with aluminum but maybe it can too.

title: Fan Buddy for MP Select Mini

description.text:
The Fan Buddy helps you during maintenance of your 3D Printer. If you're clearing a jam from your MP Select Mini, the first step is often removing the fan, which will either dangle there or sit on your print bed, depending how high the gantry is at that moment. Perhaps the torsion clips will get misplaced during your work? And will you will have a hard time finding those pesky T-nuts?

The Fan Buddy to the rescue. Slide your print-head over to the right, and clip this helpful fan-holder over the gantry. Near the right-most edge is best, as it's more stable there. When you've unclipped the fan, you can sit it securely into this little holder and not worry about the fan wires getting abraded or fatigued while you work on the nozzle.

The top of the Fan Buddy has a bit of a cup where you can place your spring-clips and T-Nuts too, so you know right where they are when you're ready to put the fan back in place.

If you're working on your hot-end while it's powered up, the fan may be spinning as you do your clean-out or adjustments. The Fan Buddy has holes to allow airflow around the fan so it's not pushing air into a brick wall (and drawing more current) as you're doing your work. Less risk of fouling the fan blades or losing bits and pieces too.

Let's face it - you're going to have that thing apart again before you know it. May as well have the Fan Buddy there to keep things under control.

title: Anet A8 Dual Mosfet & Motherboard Case with Reset Button v2

description.text:
Anet A8 Dual Mosfet Case with Reset Button v2
Follow up to my original Anet A8 Dual Mosfet Case with Reset Button found here - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2122488/
Over 2000 FREE DOWNLOADS. Now it's time to support the next project.
DOWNLOAD THE STL FILES HERE - http://de-signz.co.uk/product/anet-a8-dual-mosfet-motherboard-case-with-reset-button-v2/

This case is designed to sit at the bottom of the frame and intended to house 2 mosfets and the motherboard - oh! and with the added bonus of a reset button.

Case Size: 200mm x 135mm x 50mm with 1.6mm sides and faces.

A Short video of v2 can be found here...
https://youtu.be/Yb6Tnjm7BaI
A short video showing the reset button in action can be found here...
https://youtu.be/fnWF0Hj6eeI

Whats Changed?
After wanting to update/change the original design to be... a. Stronger, b. Easier to Print along with listening to users input the following have changed.

  1. Less Hex - I have removed alot of lower bottom case hex. I found the original to be too "hexy" causing the case to be quite weak i believe this will help strengthen up the main body... Along with making it easier to print (plus little less clean up).

  2. Added Voids (Removable) - Added extra voids for standard machine parts (z endstop slider and wire port) along with added voids for standard nuts and bolts which was causing the case to not fit smoothly.

  3. Lowered Mosfets - Lowered mosfets slightly to allow more space for power wires to the main board - i used some high amp wire that is not very flexible - this should enable a little more room,

  4. Thicker Pegs - A few users suggested making the pegs slightly thicker as a few was snapping upon screwing. i personally didnt have this issue, maybe screw size but i have thickened the base of the pegs up.

  5. Fan Clips - Little hex pieces that clips in any hex making that hex solid for you to then screw a fan or other device in. i decided to do it this way because many people use different size fans or would want to place the fan in a different location - with this piece you now can - simply press it into a hex and screw your device into it. i didnt include a screw hole because guaranteed your fans screw hole wont be align central.

Whats Not Changed? - Suggestions i didn't take into considderation this time.

  1. LCD Cable - A few users suggested to allow access for the lcd cable - with this being so slim and the cable end being so thick i didnt want to have a gaping hole in the case for a thin wire to be poking through. my solution is to feed the lcd cable behind the case and through the rear hole. this also helps keep the lecd cable flat and secured to the frame and doesnt affect the case.

  2. Cable Ports - I havent included and specific cable hole for say the extruder motors etc. this is for many reasons. everybody mounts there cables different - everyone's cables end up at different lengths by the time they get to the board. i didn't want to have big holes that would be unusable. I Personally join 2-3 hex's together by removing the joining pieces to make a larger hex where i require the wire - this works wonders and all cables fir thru the removal of just one hex separator (2 hex's)

Any issues - problems or general input leave a comment and let me know - thanks - de-signz.co.uk

Get More STL Files from DESignzUK - http://de-signz.co.uk/products/3d-files-stl/

Printer:

Anet A8

Resolution:

0.16

Infill:

100%

Notes:

I only printed with 0.16 as the case thickness is 1.6mm so 10 equal layers.
I used 100% infill as my Top/Bottom/Wall Settings are 0.8mm.

Supports are advised for the rear frame but not essential. I have attached a image of the settings i used in cura which gave me "pop out" supports.

i Printed PLA at 80mms, 190 ext, 55bed.

Avoid printing the faceplate with a standard brim (read on for "fake brim") as i struggled to remove the brim from the inner hexes on my first attempt so i advise against it - though a brim shouldn't be a problem on the case back.

I printed the front faceplate with a "brim" - i created a false brim using skirt so it applies to the outside of the faceplate only causing no silly internal hex brim! ...
To apply this false brim i set the skirt to 20 lines (this can be adjusted to suit) and i set the skirt distance to 0.01mm - good luck!

Minor Tweaks

Faceplate Clips may need to be tweaked (sanded/filed) slightly to fit (depending on your printers calibration & settings you might be lucky)

2D 2 3D

Using a 2D Vectors i created in CorelDraw i Exported Shapes as SVG and Imported to Tinkercad for Manipulation and to "3Dize"

title: Enclosure for a 17x22mm DC-DC converter/Mega upgrade

description.text:
Enclosure for a 17x22mm DC-DC converter (Updated).

Intended to be used with a Mega 2560 as a regulator upgrade.

This was added at the request of justojosegm.

It’s a box to hold this DC-DC converter : https://www.aliexpress.com/item/DC-DC-4-5V-28V-to-0-8V-20V-Step-Down-Module-Power-Supply-Good/32394108681.html

This inexpensive 22x17x4mm DC-DC converter board has no mounting holes. I’ve been using this DC-DC converter as a replacement for the standard AMS1117-5.0 800mA regulator that is found on most Mega 2560 boards.

This print is very delicate, so depending on how accurate your printer is you may have to slow the print speed down. On my Anet A8 the print speed I used for this print is 30mm/s. This updated version requires no print support and less cleanup, again depending on how accurate your printer is. It was designed with a 0.1mm spacing between the base and cover. Because of this the top may be loose if your printer is extremely accurate. You may need to sand the converter board edges square.

You obviously modify your hardware at your own risk. The easiest way to remove the regulator is to snip off all three pins, then heat up the regulator heat sink and remove the regulator. Clean up the board by removing the pins.

I replaced the standard regulator with a 3 pin XH 2.54mm connector. The SMD version of this connector is much more expensive than the right angle version, so I bought the right angle version and bent the pins to make it a SMD.

https://www.aliexpress.com/item/20sets-Lot-3-Pin-Right-Angle-Connector-Leads-Header-2-54mm-XH-3P-Kit-Housing-Pin/32557109555.html

You can clearly see from the picture showing both boards, how to wire the converter board.

Make sure you adjust the converter board output voltage before attaching it to the Mega board.

Added DC2DCBracketNoChamfer. This is used with
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2228747 MegaMountTallWConvMount.

DC2DCBracket uses M3 flat head screws.
DC2DCBracketNoChamfer uses M2.5 button head screws.

  • re-measured my shelf to be sure,
  • designed my bracket on OpenSCAD,
  • exported the file in ascii .stl,
  • converted it to a binary .stl thanks to a Ruby script provided by ByteMuse (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:39655),
  • checked that on MeshLab,
  • uploaded everything here,
  • added a reinforcement in the corner (next day),
  • reprocessed the whole loop to provide a "v2" version,
  • printed 2 items at "La fabrique du quotidien" (http://la-fabrique-du-quotidien.org/) in an ugly flashy color (but that was for a test! ;D). The design was Ok but the holes were a bit too small and the body needed to be scaled up (25x15x15 ~> 30x16x20),
  • reworked (next day) "a lot" my OpenSCAD file to make it "parametric" (play with the "parameters to tune" to see),
  • reprocessed the whole loop to provide a "v3" version,
  • reprinted (next week) 4 new items at "La fabrique du quotidien" in a transparent color,
  • fixed the brackets at home,
  • considered finally that the design is good (Ouf! ;D).
Play with the "parameters to tune" in the OpenSCAD file to generate a bracket adapted to your bookshelf. Export as .stl, slice and print.

title: AAA Cell Battery Box with Snap Lid, 1x AAA to 4xAAA Sizes

description.text:
These battery boxes have been designed with the intention that you will incorporate them into your project's 3d design directly, or you could simply cut a hole in your project and glue them in.

Each box is in 3 parts, the box itself, the lid section, and the catch which gets glued onto the lid. The catch is a separate piece because you need to print it "side on" so that the filament lies along the profile of the catch, otherwise it would just snap along the layers when you use it.

Be sure to print the box with support touching build plate only and with the cavity facing upwards, printing support in the tab or catch receptacle would be hard to remove.

Each box has a 2mm lip around the edge (actually 4mm but the inside 2mm is a fillet for strength) if you want to cut or design a hole and just glue in a separately printed box to your project.

I used CA glue (superglue) to glue the catch to the lid, works just fine. NB: Printed in PLA.

The positive and negative terminals I used are these : http://sparks.gogo.co.nz/AAA-Battery-Cell-Terminal-Pair-p669.html but you can probably get them elsewhere too. They have a backplate which is 9.6mm wide and 9.6mm high (not including the leg), the spring is about 8.7mm extended (measured from back of backplate) and 3mm compressed fully. These terminals simply press into the provided slots (it's a tight fit, use a screwdriver or something to press them down fully).

Naturally you can put the terminals in any way you wish, series, parallel, whatever, the positioning and wiring of the terminals is your business.

The catch and lid retain the cells very strongly, I could not shake them out.

Attach Catch

After printing the 3 components, put a drop of CA glue (cyanoacrylate / superglue) on the underside of the lid where you will see a small indentation that the catch is to be attached to. Clamp the catch on until the CA sets. You may find that the first time the catch isn't well glued, I find that the CA I use tends to wick into the PLA on the first application, so just add a fresh dot of glue and try again.

This was designed in OnShape you can view/copy it here.

https://cad.onshape.com/documents/be6d5f907bc0e83693f00d8c/v/349eb710b3e66a7457e40bf4
